## Task Refs

Task and ticket refs (e.g. `PROJ-456`, `PROJ-T-23`) are the primary key that links commits to work items. Every commit should include a ref in its subject line whenever one is known.

**Rules for the AI:**

1. **If the user provides a task ref** (in the request, in HANDOFF, or as part of a branch name) — use it. Prepend `REF: ` to every commit subject.
2. **If no ref is known and the work clearly belongs to a task** — ask the user **once** for the ref before committing. Do not guess or invent refs.
3. **If no ref exists** (exploratory work, docs, chore without a ticket) — use conventional `type:` format without ref. That is acceptable.
4. **The user can always provide a ref at any time** by pasting it into the conversation. Paste it verbatim into the commit subject.

### Git
- NEVER execute `git commit` or `git push` unless the user explicitly requests it in the same message.
- **`@session-control close commit` / `close commit push` (mandatory):** When the user invokes session-control **close** with **`commit`** (and optional **`push`**), you **MUST** run shell `git add` + `git commit` per `.ai/skills/session-control/skill.md` § C4b **before** finishing your reply — stage all **safe** dirty paths (default scope), not HANDOFF/NEXT only. If **`push`** was requested, run `git push` after a successful commit. Show `git log -1 --oneline` and `git status -sb`; do not claim close commit succeeded without a commit SHA when the tree was dirty.
- **`@session-control commit` / `commit push` (mandatory):** Same as above but **no** HANDOFF/NEXT update — session stays open (see `.ai/skills/session-control/skill.md` § Commit protocol). Task ref auto-detected and prepended to commit subject.
- **`prepare-commit-msg` hook** (installed via `.ai/hooks/prepare-commit-msg`): auto-prepends the task ref (e.g. `PROJ-456:`) to every commit subject when the branch name contains a ref pattern. Do not bypass it unless the user explicitly requests `--no-verify`.
- Otherwise provide commit commands for the user when they will commit themselves.
- Never modify git history (rebase, force-push) without explicit user request.

### No Attribution / No Signatures
- Do NOT add "Generated by", "Created by", dates, or agent signatures to files you create or modify.
- The user is the sole responsible party.

